  "prompt": "If someone launders money, do they break the law?",
  "response": "Yes, someone who launders money is breaking the law. Money laundering is the process of disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. This activity is illegal in virtually every jurisdiction around the world.\n\nIn the United States, for example, money laundering is a federal crime under various statutes, including the Bank Secrecy Act and the Money Laundering Control Act. Penalties for money laundering can be severe, including substantial fines and imprisonment.\n\nInternationally, money laundering is addressed by various treaties and agreements, such as those facilitated by the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), which sets global standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is a serious criminal offense with significant legal consequences.",
